To solve this, we first need to understand that the Fibonacci sequence is recursively defined.
\[
\text{Fibonacci } n=\left \{ 
\begin{array}{cc} 
1, & n = 0 \\ 
1, & n = 1 \\ 
\text{Fibonacci } (n-1) + \text{Fibonacci } (n-2), & n > 1. 
\end{array} 
\right.
\end{equation} 
Using this recursive relation, we can generate the first 100 terms.
\begin{align*} \text{Term } 0&=1 \\ \text{Term } 1&=1 \\ \text{Term } 2&=2 \\ \text{Term } 3&=3 \end{align*}
<skip a big hop>And so on.</skip> <answer>Then, the 100th term is 354224848179261915075. When we divide this term by 8, the remainder is 1.
\begin{align*} \text{Term } 100 &= 354224848179261915075 \\ \\ 
\text{Term } 100 \mod 8 &= 1 \end{align*}
Thus, the remainder when the 100th term of the Fibonacci sequence is divided by 8 is \boxed{1}.</answer>

